data.content:
Use EF Core 7+'s **`ExecuteUpdateAsync`** and **`ExecuteDeleteAsync`**. These translate directly to SQL `UPDATE`/`DELETE` statements — no entities loaded into memory:

```csharp
// Operation 1: Bulk update — single UPDATE statement
await _db.Products
    .Where(p => p.LastSoldDate < DateTime.UtcNow.AddMonths(-6))
    .ExecuteUpdateAsync(s => s.SetProperty(p => p.IsActive, false));

// Operation 2: Bulk delete — single DELETE statement
await _db.AuditLogs
    .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1))
    .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
```

**Why this is faster:**

| | Old approach | `ExecuteUpdate/Delete` |
|---|---|---|
| SQL roundtrips | 2 (SELECT + UPDATE/DELETE) | 1 |
| Memory | Loads 500K / 2M entities | Zero entities loaded |
| Change tracking | Tracks every entity | Bypassed entirely |

**Two caveats:**
1. These **bypass the change tracker** — any already-loaded entities won't reflect the change. Call after or instead of other DbContext work, not mixed in.
2. If 2M deletes in one transaction causes lock escalation, batch it:

```csharp
int deleted;
do
{
    deleted = await _db.AuditLogs
        .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1))
        .Take(10_000)
        .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
} while (deleted > 0);
```
